 stroke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round" clas=
s=3D"lucide lucide-link"><path d=3D"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-=
7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"></path><path d=3D"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 =
0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></button></div></div></h3><p>For th=
is implementation of Radiance Cascades we have an extensive list of inputs:=
</p><pre><code>// Standard fragment texel position:
varying vec2 in_TexelCoord;

// Radiance Cascades Inputs:
// Gameplay lights/occluders scene.
uniform sampler2D in_RenderScene;
// Distance Field surface to sample from.
uniform sampler2D in_DistanceField;
// Surface size of the screen/gameplay area.
uniform vec2 in_RenderExtent;
// Surface size of the cascade being rendered.
uniform vec2 in_CascadeExtent;
// Total number of cascades used.
uniform float in_CascadeCount;
// Current cascade index to render.
uniform float in_CascadeIndex;
// Probe density/spacing of cascade0.
uniform float in_CascadeLinear;
// Ray interval length of cascade0.
uniform float in_CascadeInterval;</code></pre><p><span>The first two inputs=
 </span><code>in_RenderScene</code><span> and </span><code>in_DistanceField=
</code><span> are surface textures containing the game lights/shadow caster=
s (render scene) and the distance field that represents that scene. The dis=
tance field is generated via an JFA/SDF shader which you can read about </s=
pan><a href=3D"https://mini.gmshaders.com/i/139316845/jumpflood-and-raymarc=
hing" rel=3D"">here</a><span>.</span></p><p><span>The </span><code>in_Rende=
rExtent</code><span> is two values (vec2) width and height of the scene and=
 </span><code>in_CascadeExtent</code><span> is the size of the cascade surf=
ace we=E2=80=99re rendering to. The size of the cascade depends on resoluti=
on settings:</span></p><pre><code>// Sets the cascade surface width,height =
relative to probe density.
cascade_width =3D render_width / cascade0_linear;
cascade_height =3D render_height / cascade0_linear;</code></pre><p><span>As=
 the </span><a href=3D"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1L6v1_7HY2X-LV3Ofb6o=
yTIxgEaP4LOI6/view" rel=3D"">paper outlines</a><span> (fig 8), when using 4=
x ray and 1/4x probe scaling the cascade size is constant across all cascad=
es. The </span><code>cascade0_linear</code><span> specifies the density and=
 spacing of probes as powers of two (e.g. 1, 2, 4, 8px etc. apart) a higher=
 value results in lower probe density as spacing between probes becomes lar=
ger. Values can be less than zero for even higher fidelity as you get multi=
ple probes per-pixel at </span><code>0.5 (2 probes per pixel)</code><span> =
and </span><code>0.25 (4 probes per pixel)</code><span> and </span><code>0.=
125 (8 probes per pixel) </code><span>at a much rendering higher cost.</spa=
n></p><p><span>The </span><code>in_CascadeCount</code><span> and </span><co=
de>in_CascadeIndex</code><span> are pretty self-explanatory. We pass the ca=
scade index </span><code>0=E2=80=A6N</code><span> to tell us which cascade =
pass we=E2=80=99re rendering and how many total passes are being used.</spa=
n></p><p><span>The </span><code>in_CascadeLinear</code><span> (probe spacin=
g/density) and </span><code>in_CascadeInterval</code><span> (ray interval l=
engths) are the initial cascade0 settings which get scaled 4x for each succ=
essive cascade. Cascade0 (c0) has a linear scaling of N, c1 has a scaling o=
f  N*4, c2 has a scaling of N*16, c3 has a scaling of N*64, etc.</span></p>=
<h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post">Raymarching<div class=3D"pencraft pc-displ=
ay-flex pc-alignItems-center pc-position-absolute pc-reset header-anchor-pa=
rent"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-contents pc-reset pubTheme-yiXxQA">=
<div id=3D"=C2=A7raymarching" class=3D"pencraft pc-reset header-anchor offs=
et-top"></div><button type=3D"button" aria-label=3D"Link" data-href=3D"http=
s://mini.gmshaders.com/i/143344507/raymarching" class=3D"pencraft pc-reset =
pencraft iconButton-mq_Et5 iconButtonBase-dJGHgN buttonBase-GK1x3M buttonSt=
yle-r7yGCK size_sm-G3LciD priority_secondary-S63h9o" tabindex=3D"0"><svg xm=
lns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width=3D"18" height=3D"18" viewBox=3D"0 =
0 24 24" fill=3D"none" stroke=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"2" stroke-li=
necap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round" class=3D"lucide lucide-link"><pat=
h d=3D"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"></path>=
<path d=3D"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"></=
path></svg></button></div></div></h3><p><span>We=E2=80=99ve previously visi=
ted raymarching in other posts </span><a href=3D"https://mini.gmshaders.com=
/p/voxels" rel=3D"">here </a><span>and </span><a href=3D"https://mini.gmsha=
ders.com/p/yaazarai-gi" rel=3D"">here</a><span>. The idea is the same, choo=
se a point within the scene and direction which to cast a ray and read out =
samples from the distance field at each point along the ray telling us how =
far we are away from the nearest surface=E2=80=94stop on surface hit.</span=
></p><pre><code>vec4 raymarch(vec2 point, float theta, probe_info info) {
	// Scalar for converting pixel-coordinates back to screen-space UV.
        vec2 texel =3D 1.0 / in_RenderExtent;
	// Ray component to move in the direction of theta.
	vec2 delta =3D vec2(cos(theta), -sin(theta));
	// Ray origin at interval offset starting point.
	vec2 ray =3D (point + (delta * info.offset)) * texel;								=09
=09
        // Loop for max length of interval (in event that ray SDF is near 0=
 for entire length of ray).
	for(float i =3D 0.0, df =3D 0.0, rd =3D 0.0; i &lt; info.range; i++) {
	        // Distance sample of scene converted from 2-byte encoded distance=
 field scene texture.
		df =3D V2F16(texture2D(in_DistanceField, ray).rg);
	        // Sum up total ray distance traveled (scale from distance UV to p=
ixel-coordinates).
		rd +=3D df * info.scale;			=09
	        // Move ray along its direction by SDF distance sample.
		ray +=3D (delta * df * info.scale * texel);
               =20
	        // If ray has reached range or out-of-bounds, return no-hit.
		if (rd &gt;=3D info.range || floor(ray) !=3D vec2(0.0)) break;									=
=09
	        // 2D light only cast light at their surfaces, not their volume.
		if (df &lt; EPS &amp;&amp; rd &lt; EPS &amp;&amp; in_CascadeIndex !=3D 0.=
0) return vec4(0.0);
		// On-hit return radiance from scene (with visibility term of 0--e.g. no =
visibility to merge with higher cascades).
		if (df &lt; EPS) return vec4(texture2D(in_RenderScene, ray).rgb, 0.0);
	}
=09
	// If no-hit return no radiance (with visibility term of 1--visibility to =
merge with higher cascades).
	return vec4(0.0, 0.0, 0.0, 1.0);														=09
}</code></pre><p><span>This may be atypical, however I am performing raymar=
ching in pixel space rather than UV space as it saved a lot of headache whe=
n dealing with non-square distance fields. To fix this when texture samplin=
g we get the </span><code>texel</code><span> size (texture size of 1 pixel)=
 to multiply back to UV space.</span></p><p><span>The largest change here f=
rom typical raymarching is the range and offset parameters specified for th=
e ray. Each cascade represents a different part of the radiance field and a=
s we move up the cascade chain rays get 4x longer and 4x further away. To f=
ix this we first offset the ray as </span><code>point + (delta * offset)</c=
ode><span> and then only raymarch for a fixed distance. If the ray goes off=
screen or total sampled ray distance </span><code>rd</code><span> reaches/e=
xceeds the ray=E2=80=99s interval range we terminate the ray.</span></p><p>=
<span>The second change is that in 2D light volumes only emit light from th=
eir surface edge, not from within (this otherwise causes artifacts). If the=
 ray distance </span><code>rd</code><span> is zero AND the ray starts with =
a distance field sample </span><code>df</code><span> of zero the ray starts=
 within a ray volume and must terminate.</span></p><p><span>The final chang=
e is that all distance field samples get scaled by the diagonal of the rend=
er width and height: </span><code>length(in_RenderExtent)</code><span>. The=
 </span><a href=3D"https://github.com/Yaazarai/GMShaders-Radiance-Cascades/=
blob/main/RadianceCascades-Optimized/shaders/Shd_DistanceField/Shd_Distance=
Field.fsh" rel=3D"">distance field shader</a><span> calculates all of its d=
istances in pixel coordinates and then scales them back down by this diagon=
al scale back to UV space to fit within the 2-byte float precision when sto=
ring them in the texture. This avoids scaling issues by NOT calculating dis=
tance in UV space which become skewed. In UV space the upper/lower bounds o=
f UVs are </span><code>0.0</code><span> and </span><code>1.0</code><span> f=
or both x and y axis. This becomes a problem when calculating distances bec=
ause the x and y axis have different widths and heights.</span></p><h3 clas=
s=3D"header-anchor-post">Probe/Ray Memory Layout &amp; Abstraction<div clas=
s=3D"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-alignItems-center pc-position-absolute pc-=
reset header-anchor-parent"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-contents pc-r=
eset pubTheme-yiXxQA"><div id=3D"=C2=A7proberay-memory-layout-and-abstracti=
on" class=3D"pencraft pc-reset header-anchor offset-top"></div><button type=
=3D"button" aria-label=3D"Link" data-href=3D"https://mini.gmshaders.com/i/1=
43344507/proberay-memory-layout-and-abstraction" class=3D"pencraft pc-reset=
 pencraft iconButton-mq_Et5 iconButtonBase-dJGHgN buttonBase-GK1x3M buttonS=
tyle-r7yGCK size_sm-G3LciD priority_secondary-S63h9o" tabindex=3D"0"><svg x=
mlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width=3D"18" height=3D"18" viewBox=3D"0=
 0 24 24" fill=3D"none" stroke=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"2" stroke-l=
inecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round" class=3D"lucide lucide-link"><pa=
th d=3D"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"></path=
><path d=3D"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"><=
/path></svg></button></div></div></h3><p><span>The parameters that define t=
he probe and ray information for each pixel within the cascade are re-used =
everywhere. To make this easy I=E2=80=99ve abstracted out only the necessar=
y parameters. The </span><code>angular</code><span>/</span><code>linear</co=
de><span> resolution of the cascade, </span><code>size</code><span> of each=
 direction-first probe, the ray=E2=80=99s </span><code>probe</code><span> p=
osition corresponding to its respective spatial-probe within each direction=
-first probe, </span><code>index</code><span> of the ray to calculate theta=
 or the actual direction the ray is pointing, starting </span><code>offset<=
/code><span> away from probe center and </span><code>range</code><span> or =
length of the ray cast into the scene, and the SDF </span><code>scale</code=
><span> factor.</span></p><pre><code>struct probe_info {
    float angular;
    vec2 linear, size, probe;
    float index, offset, range, scale;
};</code></pre><p>For set up we need to define an abstract function (to mak=
e life easier) which defines our parameters for the direction-first memory =
layout. In this implementation angular resolution scales 4x, but is fixed t=
o 4 rays in cascade0 and 4x for every cascade. This isn=E2=80=99t necessary=
, but makes managing cascades easier. In fact each function within the shad=
er is an abstraction to perform its very specific task.</p><pre><code>probe=
_info cascadeTexelInfo(vec2 coord) {
	// Ray Count.
        float angular =3D pow(2.0, in_CascadeIndex);
        // Cascade Probe Spacing.
	vec2 linear =3D vec2(in_CascadeLinear * pow(2.0, in_CascadeIndex));
        // Size of Probe-Group.
	vec2 size =3D in_CascadeExtent / angular;
        // Probe-Group Index.
	vec2 probe =3D mod(floor(coord), size);
        // * spatial-xy ray-index position.
	vec2 raypos =3D floor(in_TexelCoord * angular);
        // PreAvg Index (actual =3D index * 4).
	float index =3D raypos.x + (angular * raypos.y);
        // Offset of Ray Interval (geometric sum).
	float offset =3D (in_CascadeInterval  * (1.0 - pow(4.0, in_CascadeIndex)))=
 / (1.0 - 4.0);
	// Length of Ray Interval (geometric sum).
        float range =3D in_CascadeInterval * pow(4.0, in_CascadeIndex);
        //	* light Leak Fix (minimal overlap with higher cascade).
		range +=3D length(vec2(in_CascadeLinear * pow(2.0, in_CascadeIndex+1.0)))=
;
	// Diagonal of Render Extent (for SDF scaling).
        float scale =3D length(in_RenderExtent);                           =
                     =20
	// Output probe information struct.
        return probe_info(angular * angular, linear, size, probe, index, of=
fset, range, scale);
}</code></pre><p><span>The first two parameters </span><code>angular</code>=
<span> and </span><code>linear</code><span> set number of rays (angular res=
olution) and spacing (linear resolution) and by extension the number of pro=
bes within the cascade. Remember though that we=E2=80=99re pre-averaging, s=
o the angular resolution here is actually 1/4x the actual number of rays ca=
st into the scene per cascade. Both angular and linear scale 4x=E2=80=94pow=
ers of 4=E2=80=94except that linear resolution is two-dimensional so each x=
,y dimension scales by 2x for a total scaling factor of 4x.</span></p><p><s=
pan>The </span><code>size</code><span> parameter gets the number of rays=E2=
=80=94each corresponding to their respective probe=E2=80=94within each dire=
ction-first probe. The </span><code>probe</code><span> parameter then deter=
mines the actual probe-position of the ray. The index parameter converts ou=
r two-dimensional texel coordinate into 1-dimensional array index via the <=
/span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Row-_and_column-major_order"=
 rel=3D"">row-major-order curve</a><span> or </span><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Raster_scan" rel=3D"">raster-scanline</a><span> order whi=
ch is just simple to use=E2=80=94there shouldn=E2=80=99t be any real benefi=
t to storing via </span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z-order_cu=
rve" rel=3D"">z-order curve</a><span> as lookups for merging are GPU inexpe=
nsive and not worth the added complexity.</span></p><p><span>The </span><co=
de>offset</code><span> and </span><code>range</code><span> parameters are p=
er specification where rays within each cascade gets 4x offset further away=
 and get 4xs larger using </span><a href=3D"https://youtube.com/shorts/Evbs=
k8yuoSQ?si=3DhgA1sNu09RNtwrYa" rel=3D"">geometric sequences</a><span>. Howe=
ver we also need to add a final minor overlap to the cascade interval to br=
ight the slight gap between cascades to fix light leak. This overlap is spa=
cing between probes of cascade N+1 due to the spatial transition between ca=
scades N and N+1.</span></p><p>Finally we set the SDF=E2=80=99s scaling par=
ameter for reading out pixel-space distances from our distance field shader=
. The SDF scales itself by the diagonal of the screen resolution to convert=
 pixel-space distances to UV space while fitting in the 2-byte precision of=
 the Distance field texture. This is done by calculating length of the vect=
or formed by the width and height of the screen.</p><h3 class=3D"header-anc=
hor-post">Merging with Cascade N+1<div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-flex pc=
-alignItems-center pc-position-absolute pc-reset header-anchor-parent"><div=
 class=3D"pencraft pc-display-contents pc-reset pubTheme-yiXxQA"><div id=3D=
"=C2=A7merging-with-cascade-n1" class=3D"pencraft pc-reset header-anchor of=
fset-top"></div><button type=3D"button" aria-label=3D"Link" data-href=3D"ht=
tps://mini.gmshaders.com/i/143344507/merging-with-cascade-n1" class=3D"penc=
raft pc-reset pencraft iconButton-mq_Et5 iconButtonBase-dJGHgN buttonBase-G=
K1x3M buttonStyle-r7yGCK size_sm-G3LciD priority_secondary-S63h9o" tabindex=
=3D"0"><svg xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width=3D"18" height=3D"18"=
 viewBox=3D"0 0 24 24" fill=3D"none" stroke=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=
=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round" class=3D"lucide l=
ucide-link"><path d=3D"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.=
72 1.71"></path><path d=3D"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.=
07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></button></div></div></h3><p><span>The final puz=
zle piece is merging the current cascade with the next highest cascade. </s=
pan><code>Direction-First</code><span> ordering to enable hardware interpol=
ation and </span><code>Pre-Averaging</code><span> make this trivial, cuttin=
g down our merge samples from 16 (4 per probe) down to 1 single texture sam=
ple. Nice!</span></p><pre><code>vec4 merge(vec4 rinfo, float index, probe_i=
nfo pinfo) {
	// For any radiance with zero-alpha do not merge (highest cascade also can=
not merge).
	if (rinfo.a =3D=3D 0.0 || in_CascadeIndex &gt;=3D in_CascadeCount - 1.0)
	        // Return non-merged radiance (invert alpha to correct alpha from =
raymarch ray-visibility term).
		return vec4(rinfo.rgb, 1.0 - rinfo.a);

	// Angular resolution of cascade N+1 for probe lookups.
	float angularN1 =3D pow(2.0, in_CascadeIndex + 1.0);
	// Size of probe group of cascade N+1 (N+1 has 1/4 total probe count or 1/=
2 each x,y axis).
	vec2 sizeN1 =3D pinfo.size * 0.5;
	// Get the probe group correlated to the ray index passed of the current c=
ascade ray we're merging with.
	vec2 probeN1 =3D vec2(mod(index, angularN1), floor(index / angularN1)) * s=
izeN1;
	// Interpolated probe position in cascade N+1 (layouts match but with 1/2 =
count, probe falls into its interpolated position by default).
	vec2 interpUVN1 =3D pinfo.probe * 0.5;
	// Clamp interpolated probe position away from edge to avoid hardware inte=
prolation affecting merge lookups from adjacet probe groups.
	vec2 clampedUVN1 =3D max(vec2(1.0), min(interpUVN1, sizeN1 - 1.0));
	// Final lookup cascade position of the interpolated merge lookup.
	vec2 probeUVN1 =3D probeN1 + clampedUVN1 + 0.25;
	// Interpolated texture lookup of the merge sample.
	vec4 interpolated =3D texture2D(gm_BaseTexture, probeUVN1 * (1.0 / in_Casc=
adeExtent));
	// Return original radiance input and merge with lookup sample.
	return rinfo + interpolated;
}</code></pre><p>The first if-statement check here is crucial. We want to a=
void merging rays in two separate cases:</p><ol><li><p>If the current ray a=
lready has radiance by hitting a surface=E2=80=94only terminated rays with =
no-hit need to merge because they found no scene radiance. Also any ray in =
cascade0 with a hit must have its alpha component inverted as the ray-visib=
ility term is stored in the alpha component as 1 for no-hit and 0 for hit. =
If you don=E2=80=99t invert the alpha all light volumes within the scene wi=
ll be black.</p></li><li><p>We never merge rays if we=E2=80=99re in the hig=
hest cascade. If there is no higher cascade, there is no cascade N+1 to mer=
ge with.</p></li></ol><p>When merging for each ray we merge with 16 rays of=
 cascade N+1, lookup each N+1 probe and the 4 corresponding rays in this di=
rection, average, then interpolate. The averaging is done and hardware inte=
rpolation is setup, so all we have to do is find the closest top-left N+1 p=
robe and add an offset between the 4 probes for our weight to get the inter=
polated sample.</p><p><span>If you look back at figure 1 for merging you ca=
n see that the interpolation weight is relative to the current probe=E2=80=
=99s position between all N+1 probes, which is </span><code>0.25, 0.25</cod=
e><span> (closest to top-left), </span><code>0.75, 0.25</code><span> (close=
st to top-right), </span><code>0.25, 0.75</code><span> (closest to bottom-l=
eft) and finally </span><code>0.75, 0.75</code><span> (closest to bottom-ri=
ght). These weights are set because of the spatial density and positioning =
of this cascades probes are evenly distributed between probes of cascade N+=
1.</span></p><p><span>Now we need to get a little bit of information about =
cascade N+1, the angular resolution or </span><code>angularN1</code><span> =
and size of each directional probe or </span><code>sizeN1</code><span> and =
the direction-first probe or </span><code>probeN1</code><span> correspondin=
g to the </span><code>index</code><span> (direction/theta index) of the ray=
 we=E2=80=99re merging. This is done by converting our </span><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Row-_and_column-major_order" rel=3D"">row-major=
-order curve</a><span> ray-index back to spatial index and then multiplying=
 by the direction-first probe size to get the top-left probe position in th=
e cascade.</span></p><ul><li><p><em><strong>NOTE:</strong></em><span> that =
with pre-averaged rays if we multiply our ray-index by 4 to get the actual =
index, this gives us the same resolution as the pre-averaged rays of cascad=
e N+1. See figure below for an illustration of how index blocks of varying =
resolutions line up.</span></p></li></ul><div class=3D"captioned-image-cont=
ainer"><figure><a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://substackcdn.com/image/f=
